Notification System Design
Stage 1
So the frontend dev on my team needs to know what APIs exist so they can show notifications to students after they log in. I sat down and thought about what all a notification screen actually needs to do and came up with this.
What the platform needs to support
From a student's point of view, they should be able to:

see all their notifications when they open the app
click one and have it marked as read
see a little badge showing how many unread ones they have
filter by type — like only placements or only events
get new notifications instantly without having to refresh the page

That last one needs WebSockets, rest are normal REST endpoints.

Base URL
http://localhost:5000/api
Auth is pre-handled so I'm just passing the student's ID in a header called X-Student-ID to know whose notifications to serve.

Endpoints
GET /notifications
Pulls the notification list for a student. Has pagination and optional type filter.
Headers:
Content-Type: application/json
X-Student-ID: <student_id>
Query params:

page — default 1
limit — default 20, max 100
notification_type — optional, values: Event / Result / Placement

Example: GET /api/notifications?page=1&limit=10&notification_type=Placement
Response 200:
json{
  "success": true,
  "page": 1,
  "limit": 10,
  "total": 3,
  "notifications": [
    {
      "id": "b283218f-ea5a-4b7c-93a9-1f2f240d64b0",
      "type": "Placement",
      "message": "CSX Corporation hiring",
      "timestamp": "2026-04-22T17:51:18Z",
      "isRead": false
    }
  ]
}

GET /notifications/:id
For when a student clicks on a specific notification.
Headers:
Content-Type: application/json
X-Student-ID: <student_id>
Response 200:
json{
  "success": true,
  "notification": {
    "id": "81589ada-0ad3-4f77-9554-f52fb558e09d",
    "type": "Event",
    "message": "farewell",
    "timestamp": "2026-04-22T17:51:06Z",
    "isRead": false
  }
}
Response 404:
json{
  "success": false,
  "error": "notification not found"
}

PATCH /notifications/:id/read
Marks one notification as read when opened.
Headers:
Content-Type: application/json
X-Student-ID: <student_id>
Response 200:
json{
  "success": true,
  "message": "marked as read",
  "id": "81589ada-0ad3-4f77-9554-f52fb558e09d"
}

PATCH /notifications/read-all
For the "mark all as read" button.
Headers:
Content-Type: application/json
X-Student-ID: <student_id>
Response 200:
json{
  "success": true,
  "message": "all marked as read",
  "updatedCount": 7
}

GET /notifications/unread-count
Just the count — so the navbar badge doesn't have to load the whole list.
Headers:
Content-Type: application/json
X-Student-ID: <student_id>
Response 200:
json{
  "success": true,
  "unreadCount": 5
}

Real-time — WebSocket
I went with WebSockets over SSE because it's two-way, so later if we need the client to send something back (like an ack), we already have that channel open.
Connection: ws://localhost:5000/ws/notifications?studentId=<student_id>
On the server side I just maintain a plain object mapping student IDs to their socket connection. When a notification gets created for a student, I look them up in that map and push it directly if they're online. If they're offline it just stays in the DB and they'll get it on next load.
What the server sends when a new notification comes in:
json{
  "event": "new_notification",
  "data": {
    "id": "1cfce5ee-ad37-4894-8946-d707627176a5",
    "type": "Event",
    "message": "tech-fest",
    "timestamp": "2026-04-22T17:50:06Z",
    "isRead": false
  }
}
Client pings every 30s to keep the connection alive:
json{ "event": "ping" }
Server responds:
json{ "event": "pong" }

Errors
All errors look the same across every endpoint:
json{
  "success": false,
  "error": "what went wrong",
  "code": 404
}
400 → bad input, 404 → not found, 500 → server broke
